Here is the complete diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

**Root cause: AP-066 — Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text.**

The SCSS for `.logo` already has a comment that reads *"must never wrap or shrink"* and sets `flex-shrink: 0`. The comment is right. The code is wrong. Here's the actual failure chain:

1. `.navInner` is `display: flex; justify-content: space-between`. At narrow widths, flex distributes pressure across all children.
2. `.logo` has `flex-shrink: 0` — correct — but the **flex container itself** (`.navInner`) has no `min-width` floor, so the outer flex row can still compress.
3. The critical gap: **`.logo` is an `<a>` element containing two children: `.logoMark` (a block) and `.logoText` (a span with `white-space: nowrap`)**. The `white-space: nowrap` is correctly on `.logoText`, but the *parent link* `.logo` itself has no `white-space: nowrap` and **no explicit `min-width`**. When the flex row is squeezed below the intrinsic content width of `.logo`, the browser still tries to wrap *inside* the flex item because the flex item has no `overflow: visible` or `min-content` floor protecting the multi-child inline layout inside it.
4. The `.links` side correctly has `min-width: 0` to absorb compression — but there is nothing anchoring the left side as permanently uncompressible in a two-axis way. `flex-shrink: 0` prevents the flex item from *shrinking*, but if the outer container is itself squeezed below `min-content` for `.logo`, the browser resolves the conflict by wrapping the mark + text inside the item.

The three-part fix is:
- Add `white-space: nowrap` directly on `.logo` (the flex item / link element), not just on the inner span — this is the canonical CSS idiom: clamp wrapping at the container, not just a leaf.
- Add `overflow: visible` so the nowrap doesn't clip anything.
- Codify **AP-066** with this exact pattern as the authoritative rule, and add a new named principle — **Identity Text Priority** — to `branding.md`.

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

The changes are surgical — three lines on `.logo`, one clarifying comment tightening on `.logoText`:

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);

  &::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    height: 10px;
    transform: translateY(100%);
    backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
}

.navInner {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  max-width: $elan-container-wide;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);

  @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
    padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
  }
}

.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;
  text-decoration: none;
  // ── IDENTITY TEXT PRIORITY (AP-066) ───────────────────────────────────────
  // The logo is the site's single hardest identity line. It is unconditionally
  // rigid — it NEVER wraps, shrinks, or yields to flex pressure at any viewport.
  // Three properties work together as a unit:
  //   flex-shrink: 0   → the flex item cannot lose width
  //   white-space: nowrap → the mark + text inside cannot fold onto two lines
  //   min-width: max-content → the item claims exactly its intrinsic width as
  //                            an unbreakable floor; no flex algorithm can give
  //                            it less without violating a hard constraint
  // All three are required. Removing any one of them creates a wrapping path.
  // The tagline on the right (.links side) is the designated yielding surface —
  // it absorbs all overflow by wrapping, capped at 2 lines. See .tagline below.
  flex-shrink: 0;
  white-space: nowrap;
  min-width: max-content;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    .logoMark {
      background-color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }

    .logoText {
      color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }
  }
}

.logoMark {
  display: inline-block;
  height: calc($portfolio-type-2xl * 1.2);
  aspect-ratio: 1;
  flex-shrink: 0;
  background-color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  mask-image: url('/images/yg-logo.svg');
  mask-size: contain;
  mask-repeat: no-repeat;
  @include transition-fast;
}

.logoText {
  font-family: $portfolio-font-serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-2xl;
  font-weight: $portfolio-weight-regular;
  line-height: $portfolio-leading-snug;
  color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  letter-spacing: $portfolio-tracking-tight;
  // white-space: nowrap is inherited from .logo — declared there as the
  // canonical containment point. Kept here only as documentation.
  white-space: nowrap;
  @include transition-fast;
}

.links {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--portfolio-spacer-3x);
  // .links is the designated yielding surface. It shrinks freely and passes
  // compression down to .tagline (which wraps at 2 lines) rather than pushing
  // back on .logo. min-width: 0 overrides the flex default of min-width: auto
  // so this item can go below its intrinsic content size.
  min-width: 0;
}

.link {
  font-family: var(--portfolio-font-sans);
  font-size: var(--portfolio-type-sm);
  font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-regular);
  color: var(--portfolio-text-secondary);
  text-decoration: none;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
  }
}

.linkActive {
  color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
  font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-medium);
}

.tagline {
  @include body-sm;
  color: var(--portfolio-text-secondary);
  // The tagline is the designated soft edge of the nav. It yields to narrow
  // viewports by wrapping onto a second line, capped at 2 lines so it never
  // invades the site content below. It can wrap. The logo cannot.
  min-width: 0;
  text-align: right;
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
  line-clamp: 2;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

**What changed vs the original:**
| Property | Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| `.logo { white-space }` | not set | `nowrap` | Prevents mark+text from line-breaking inside the flex item |
| `.logo { min-width }` | not set | `max-content` | Gives the flex algorithm a hard floor equal to the logo's intrinsic width — flex cannot compress below it |
| `.logo { flex-shrink }` | `0` | `0` (unchanged) | Kept; required to complete the three-property unit |
| Comments | vague intent | explicit AP-066 citation | Future agents know exactly why all three properties exist together |

---

### 2. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — Amend AP-066

Replace the existing AP-066 entry with this expanded version that captures the three-property rule and makes the "designated yielding surface" pattern explicit:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE**
**Last amended:** 2026-[today] (three-property rule + "designated yielding surface" pattern codified from FB-146 second occurrence)

**Trigger:** A flex row contains an identity text element (logo name, site title, brand
wordmark) alongside secondary content. The secondary content is given `min-width: 0`
to absorb compression, but the identity element is protected with only `flex-shrink: 0`
— without `white-space: nowrap` AND `min-width: max-content` on the same element.

**Why it's wrong:**
`flex-shrink: 0` prevents the flex *item* from losing width in the flex algorithm, but
it does not prevent the browser from wrapping inline content *inside* the item. When
the flex container is squeezed below the natural layout width, the browser can still
break the logo mark and logo text onto separate lines within that item's box. The
result is a two-line logo — the exact failure this protection was meant to prevent.

The three properties are a unit — removing any one creates a wrapping path:

| Property | What it blocks |
|---|---|
| `flex-shrink: 0` | Flex algorithm cannot shrink the item |
| `white-space: nowrap` | Inline content inside the item cannot line-break |
| `min-width: max-content` | Flex algorithm cannot give the item less than its intrinsic content width (blocks the edge case where `flex-shrink: 0` is overridden by an ancestor or the browser's min-content resolution) |

**Correct alternative:**

```scss
// On the identity element (logo link, brand wordmark, etc.):
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;
  white-space: nowrap;
  min-width: max-content;
}

// On the yielding sibling — the element that absorbs all overflow:
.links {
  min-width: 0;     // overrides flex default of min-width: auto
  // children inside .links (e.g. .tagline) can wrap freely
}
```

**The "designated yielding surface" principle:** Every flex row that contains an
identity element must also designate a sibling as the compression absorber. That
sibling gets `min-width: 0` and its children are allowed to wrap or truncate. The
identity element never compromises; the yielding surface absorbs everything.

**Examples in this codebase:**
- `Navigation.module.scss`: `.logo` (rigid) / `.links > .tagline` (yields, wraps 2 lines)

**Related:** See FB-146 (nav logo wrap), FB-150 (experience column company names).
```

---

### 3. `docs/design/branding.md` — Add §10: Identity Text Priority

Add a new section to the end of `branding.md`. This elevates the rule from a CSS anti-pattern to a named design principle that applies across any identity-carrying text element:

```markdown
---

## 10. Identity Text Priority

**Source:** FB-146, AP-066

### 10.1 The Rule

**Identity text — any text that carries the site's core identity signal — must never wrap to two lines at any viewport width, under any flex or grid pressure.** This is not a CSS preference; it is a design principle with the same status as zero corner radius (§1).

| Text element | Classification | Wrapping rule |
|---|---|---|
| "Yilan Gao" (nav logo) | **Identity text** | Never wraps. Ever. |
| Nav link labels (if any) | **Identity-adjacent** | Should not wrap; truncate with `text-overflow: ellipsis` if necessary |
| Tagline / role blurb | **Secondary** | May wrap, capped at 2 lines |
| All other body content | **Content** | Wraps freely |

### 10.2 Mechanical Implementation

Every identity text element must carry all three of the following CSS properties simultaneously. They are a unit — removing any one creates a wrapping path:

```scss
.identity-element {
  flex-shrink: 0;        // Item cannot be compressed by flex algorithm
  white-space: nowrap;   // Inline content inside cannot line-break
  min-width: max-content; // Item claims its full intrinsic width as a hard floor
}
```

See AP-066 for the full explanation of why all three are required.

### 10.3 The Designated Yielding Surface

For every identity element that lives in a flex row, there must be a sibling element
that is explicitly designated as the compression absorber. That sibling gets
`min-width: 0` and its children are allowed to wrap or truncate. The identity element
never compromises; the yielding surface absorbs everything.

**Current assignments:**

| Rigid (never wraps) | Yielding surface |
|---|---|
| `.logo` (nav) | `.links > .tagline` — wraps freely, max 2 lines |

When adding new flex rows to the nav or any identity-bearing shell surface, this
assignment must be made explicitly before shipping. A flex row with an identity element
and no named yielding surface is incomplete.
```

---

## Principle

**AP-066 — Identity Text Priority.** The core rule: `flex-shrink: 0` alone is insufficient to protect a multi-child flex item from internal line-wrapping. You need all three properties as a unit: `flex-shrink: 0` (item can't lose width), `white-space: nowrap` (children can't break lines), `min-width: max-content` (the floor is the intrinsic content width, not zero). The pattern has two halves — every rigid identity element requires a named *yielding surface* sibling that absorbs the compression instead. The tagline can wrap. The name cannot.
